She turned to a blank page and noted the date. Below, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Do you reread memories?", Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded her head. "Do you think they will let you out for Christmas? It's not much longer."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. No. Ivory was right. The Ice King never let Kari out, because she was "a mistake" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only daughter of the family, otherwise only composed of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she reported her non-binary condition, it was as if the world also changed. They assigned her tasks that condemned her to solitude, as punishment for her difference.
She had to stay in service to the princess, but that wasn't very bad, because it made her an friend.
"It's almost your birthday, I think?", asked Ivory, remembering that the princess's birthday was just a few days away. Kari nodded her head, a sad spark in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" While asking the question, she remembered what she had replied to her last time.
No, Kari tapped twice. Ivory knew that it was a difficult topic for her. It was the day when she was confined to her room and her mother was banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but she remembered the indignation of the servants and the inhabitants. She had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Well... what do you want to do?", she asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed Ivory a piece of paper. But when she glanced at it...
Painting canvas 15 cm x 15 cm
Blank, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Do you want me to find those things for you?", said Ivory, turning towards the silent princess who was frantically tapping away, shaking her curls back and forth. "Yes?" She let out a slight giggle at seeing the usually reserved princess get passionate about something. It was the first time she asked for something unrelated to books and not found in her room.
"Alright. See you later?", proposed Ivory, getting up and making her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari acquiesça and plunged back into her memories by wrapping herself up in her thick quilt again.
She stepped out of the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that weren't in her domain, such as paint.
She turned back through the corridors, trying not to listen to the murmurs of the maids.
"I've heard she was possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes into this room."
"I've heard she eats children in this room."
"She resembles a man, doesn't she?"
Ivory covered her ears, as trying to ignore them wasn't working. She headed towards the royal painter's room, which was located east, second door to the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was also worked as Kari's. It displayed a white dragon, one of the 6 primordial dragons, which according to the legend had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to expose it on his door. He liked the story.
Ivory opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Splatters of paint everywhere, scattered pencils and papers in the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. Surprisingly, she saw nothing of that. The room was clean and there was a red velvet backdrop with a stool in front of it. On the stool, Prince Aquilo was sitting, getting his portrait taken.
"Ah, good morning, Ivory! You're here to watch your future king pose for a portrait?", Aquilo asked Ivory, giving her a wink.
"Pardon, little prince", she replied, ignoring him partially, to search for the objects that her silent friend wanted. "I'm here just to get supplies".
"Ah, the little girl will leave very soon?", asked Aquilo, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me". Ivory had found the art supplies from her list and placed them in a box that she had found. "And I'm not a girl".
The prince hadn't thought of that, however. "Oh my dear, you know well that it's just a phase! It will pass when you grow up!", he muttered.
"I must go", she said, suddenly feeling uneasy, due to the prince's words, which reminded her of all the bad things people said about her gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"You're leaving already?" The Prince appeared at the door immediately, ignoring the complaints of the royal painter.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" he scolded him.
"No one will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he wants to live." He turned back to the painter for a second, then leaned towards Ivory. "How about a romantic rendezvous?" Ivory shuddered. Certainly, she had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, let alone the heir to the throne.
"Don't you know what the word 'no' means?" she threw, pushing the prince aside.
"Oh no," replied Aquilo, smiling. Obviously, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what this word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want a romantic rendezvous with me rather than with others? You must have a good hundred suitors?"
He interrupted her, still smiling all the while: "500, to be exact". He threw his hair back, making it fly through the cold air.
"So, why me rather than another? I'm the threat to the palace." She wrapped her arms around her body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
